```json
{
  "application": "SLURM",
  "details": {
    "job_name": "omp_photon",
    "partition": "defq",
    "time": "5:00:00",
    "nodes": 1,
    "tasks": 1,
    "tasks_per_node": 1,
    "memory": "150000",
    "cpus_per_task": 80,
    "exclusive": true,
    "mail_type": "ALL",
    "mail_user": "j.schenke@hzdr.de",
    "output_file": "log.ob.slurm-%A_%a.out",
    "error_file": "err.ob.slurm-%A_%a.out",
    "environment_variables": {
      "alpaka_DIR": "/home/schenk24/workspace/alpaka/install/",
      "CC": "icc",
      "CXX": "icpc",
      "KMP_AFFINITY": "verbose,compact"
    },
    "modules": [
      "git",
      "intel",
      "cmake",
      "boost",
      "python"
    ],
    "software": [
      "bench"
    ],
    "input_files": [
      "../../../data_pool/px_101016/allpede_250us_1243__B_000000.dat",
      "../../../data_pool/px_101016/gainMaps_M022.bin",
      "../../../data_pool/px_101016/Insu_6_tr_1_45d_250us__B_000000.dat",
      "/bigdata/hplsim/production/jungfrau-photoncounter/reference/cluster_energy.bin",
      "/bigdata/hplsim/production/jungfrau-photoncounter/reference/bin/photon.bin",
      "/bigdata/hplsim/production/jungfrau-photoncounter/reference/maxValues.bin",
      "/bigdata/hplsim/production/jungfrau-photoncounter/reference/sum.bin",
      "/bigdata/hplsim/production/jungfrau-photoncounter/reference/clusters.bin"
    ],
    "output_files": [
      "cores$I"
    ]
  }
}
```

This script is running a job submission using SLURM. 

The script uses the `SBATCH` command to submit a job to SLURM, specifying various parameters like job name, time limit, number of nodes, tasks, memory, and other settings.

The script also sets several environment variables: `alpaka_DIR`, `CC`, `CXX`, and `KMP_AFFINITY`. These variables are used to configure the environment for the software the script runs.

The script then runs a loop iterating through different values for `OMP_NUM_THREADS`.  In each iteration, the script runs a program named `bench` with various input data files and outputs results to files named `cores$I`.

The details of the `bench` program are not provided in the script, but the input and output files give some insights into its functionality. It seems to be a performance benchmark that tests different numbers of OpenMP threads.
